<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-10-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-10-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="349" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d349">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 493.11A/5.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Calhoun</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-10-15"><hi rend="italic">October 15,
                                1910</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Mr. Calhoun says the Wai-wu Pu has once more requested that the consul
                            general at Hankow be given power to negotiate a settlement of the
                            Changsha claims, and says in view of the fact that this <pb facs="0464" n="352" xml:id="pg_352"/> has been repeatedly urged and as all
                            claims have long since been filed, suggests that local settlement be
                            effected through the consul general if the claims meet with the approval
                            of the department.</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>